1. call()

call() is a method that invokes a function immediately and allows you to explicitly set the value of this. Arguments are passed individually.

2. apply()

apply() is a method that invokes a function immediately and allows you to explicitly set the value of this. Arguments are passed as an array (or array-like object).

3. bind()

bind() is a method that does not invoke the function immediately. Instead, it returns a new function with this permanently bound to the specified object.


First understand one thing.

Problem
function introduce() {
    console.log(this.name);
}

Now

let person = {
    name: "Lucky"
};

How can we make

this = person

JavaScript gives us

call()
apply()
bind()
call()

Runs the function immediately.

Arguments are passed one by one.

function greet(city) {
    console.log(this.name + " from " + city);
}

let person = {
    name: "Lucky"
};

greet.call(person, "Mathura");

Output

Lucky from Mathura
apply()

Exactly same as call()

Difference

Arguments are passed inside an array.

greet.apply(person, ["Mathura"]);

Output

Lucky from Mathura
bind()

This one is different.

It does NOT run immediately.

Instead,

It returns a new function.

let newFunction = greet.bind(person, "Mathura");

newFunction();

Output

Lucky from Mathura
Easy Memory Trick
call()

Runs immediately
Arguments separately

-----------------------

apply()

Runs immediately
Arguments inside array

-----------------------

bind()

Does NOT run
Returns a new function
Interview Answer

call() and apply() invoke the function immediately. bind() returns a new function. call() takes arguments separately, whereas apply() takes them as an array.

